There are three kinds of teeth——serrated or Th mm. continuous or projecting: serrated teeth closing to- gether like the teeth of a comb, so as not to be worn away by direct collision, as in snakes, fishes and dogs; continuous‚ as in man and the horse· , proj ecting, as in the boar, hippopotamus and elephant. Of continu- ous teeth those that separate the food (incisors), are called the broad or sharp teeth, those that masticate it double teeth‚ and those be- tween these dog-teeth. The latter are longest in creatures with serrated teeth. Continuous teeth are either in both jaws, as with the horse, 01· else there are no front teeth in the upper jaw, 35 with oxen and sheep and all the ruminants. The goat has no upper teeth except the pair in front. Species having serrated teeth have no projecting teeth‚ and a female rarely has them, and when she has them does not use them3 consequently though boars gore, sows bite. No species with horns has projecting teeth, but all have eux-ved ones; all the other species have solid teeth.
